    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Double Standard</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Conan D Owen letter scores stereotypical treatment of Scandinavians in July 13 article on their use of cell phones</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The hypocrisy of The New York Times never ceases to amaze me. A publication that goes out of its way to be sensitive and inclusive to all the politically correct groups seems to think nothing about portraying Scandinavians in stereotypical terms.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The hypocrisy of The New York Times never ceases to amaze me. A publication that goes out of its way to be sensitive and inclusive to all the politically correct groups seems to think nothing about portraying Scandinavians in stereotypical terms.</p>
        <p>''Wireless Valhalla: Hints of the Cellular Future'' (July 13) used four cartoons to depict Scandinavians as blond, horned-helmet-wearing, armor-clad Vikings. Would The New York Times ever illustrate an article on black Americans with stereotypical images? So why the double standard when it comes to white Europeans? The Times seems to think only certain stereotypes are offensive. Before you run another editorial denouncing stereotyping by others, take a look in the mirror and deal with your own hypocrisy first.</p>
        <p>CONAN D. OWEN  Washington</p>
      </block>
